@SConwaySmith Simon, literally every national science agency on earth (including the likes of NASA) disagrees with you. 

The physics of heat-trapping greenhouse gases have been established since the 19th century.

99.9% of studies agree: humans caused climate change https://t.co/WVQSyuEJx2

@GeorgeMonbiot It's almost certainly too late to avoid 1.5°C, and probably 2°C.

But we can avoid the civilisation-ending rises of 5 or 6°C. 

We will lose much of the world's wildlife, but humanity will persist, and transition to a more sustainable system by 2100. Then we can start to rebuild.

@JamesMGeary Very interesting. That's about 894 km/s.
For comparison, the escape velocity needed to exit the Milky Way is 550 km/s.
The fastest known star is S5-HVS1, which moves at 1,755 km/s (3,930,000 mph) after being slingshotted out of our galaxy by Sagittarius A*.

